article.description: Ticha Penicheiro said New York was "beatable." On Tuesday, the Liberty proved her wrong.
article.headline: Liberty hit 10 treys; 'Spoon plays 14 minutes
article.linkText: New York guards get hot, lead Liberty past Monarchs
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs ended a
homestand with a rout and sent the New York Liberty limping home.

Tangela Smith scored 17 points Thursday night to lead the
Monarchs to a 73-47 victory over road-weary New York.

The Monarchs (6-7) have won three straight and now will head out
on a five-game road trip that begins Saturday in Seattle. The
Liberty, who have lost eight of nine since a 6-1 start, will host
Sacramento on Tuesday as part of a five-game homestand.

"We've played 11 of our 16 games on the road, games like this
will happen," New York coach Richie Adubato said. "I don't know
if it's good we play them so soon. We have a lot of problems to
solve in regards to their play."

The Monarchs scored 14 straight points in the first half and
held New York scoreless for over nine minutes in taking a 24-8
lead.

"We play five games on the road, so we'll see if we can
continue playing this well," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said.
"It will be tough. But we have the kind of game, rebounding and
defense, that can win on the road."

Becky Hammon made a 3-pointer to end the Liberty drought, but
New York (7-9) made only two field goals in the final 14:34 and
trailed 32-13 at halftime. It was the Liberty's lowest scoring
first half in team history.

"We tried to run them, they were tired," Smith said. "That
played a big role in this win. Having a win like this was real
nice, we haven't had one like this all year."

The Monarchs' reserves scored 31 points, including 10 each from
Chantelle Anderson and Rebekkah Brunson. Yolanda Griffith also
scored 10.

Hamchetou Maiga had eight points, and Ticha Penicheiro added
five points, seven assists and six rebounds.

Vickie Johnson led New York with 17 points and Shameka Christon
had 10. Elena Baranova, who had 27 points in an overtime loss
Tuesday in Los Angeles, shot 3 of 12 and had seven points and nine
rebounds.

In the first half, the Liberty went 6-for-28 and committed 12
turnovers.

Smith scored seven first-half points for Sacramento, which
trailed only in the opening minutes. The Monarchs opened the second
half by making five of six shots in taking a 42-14 lead with 16:33
remaining.

New York had only nine players and was missing starters Crystal
Robinson and Tari Phillips.
